  "prompt": "What is the difference between active voice and passive voice?",
  "response": "The difference between active voice and passive voice lies in the focus of the sentence and the placement of the subject and the object.\n\n1. **Active Voice**:\n   - **Structure**: Subject + Verb + Object\n   - **Focus**: The subject performs the action.\n   - **Example**: \"The chef cooked the meal.\"\n     - *Subject*: The chef\n     - *Verb*: cooked\n     - *Object*: the meal\n\n2. **Passive Voice**:\n   - **Structure**: Object + Form of \"to be\" + Past Participle + (by Subject)\n   - **Focus**: The action is performed on the object, and the subject can be either included or omitted.\n   - **Example**: \"The meal was cooked by the chef.\"\n     - *Object*: The meal\n     - *Form of \"to be\"*: was\n     - *Past Participle*: cooked\n     - *(Optional Subject)*: by the chef\n\nIn summary, the active voice emphasizes the subject performing the action, while the passive voice emphasizes the action being performed on the object, possibly deemphasizing or omitting the subject.",
